The '''geocorona''' is the luminous part of the outermost region of the [[Earth's atmosphere]], the [[exosphere]]. It is seen primarily via [[ultraviolet|far-ultraviolet]] [[light]] ([[Lyman series|Lyman-alpha]]) from the [[Sun]] that is [[Scattering|scattered]] from [[neutral hydrogen]]. It extends to at least 15.5 [[Earth radii]]. The geocorona has been studied from [[outer space]] by the [[Astrid (satellites)|Astrid satellites]] and the [[Galileo spacecraft]] (among others), using its ultraviolet [[spectrometer]] ([[UVS]]) during an [[Earth]] [[Planetary flyby|flyby]].
