{{coord|21|N|157|W|display=title}} {{Infobox ecoregion |name = Hawaiian tropical dry forests |image = Starr_040220-0314_Santalum_paniculatum.jpg |image_size = 300 |image_caption = An {{okina}}iliahi (''[[Santalum]] [[Santalum paniculatum|paniculatum]]'') at [[Hawaii Volcanoes National Park|Hawai{{okina}}i Volcanoes National Park]]. |country = [[United States]] ([[Hawaii]]) |border = [[Hawaiian tropical low shrublands]] |border1 = [[Hawaiian tropical rainforests]] |border2 = [[Hawaiian tropical high shrublands]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cas.vanderbilt.edu/bioimages/ecoregions/70202frame.htm |title=Hawaii Tropical Dry Forests |work=Bioimages |publisher=Vanderbilt University |accessdate=2011-11-19}}</ref> |bird_species = |mammal_species = |plant_species = |habitat_loss = |habitat_loss_ref = |protected = |protected_ref = |area = 6600 |biome = [[Tropical and subtropical dry broadleaf forests]] |conservation = Critical/Endangered<ref name="WWF">{{WWF ecoregion|id=oc0202|name=Hawaii tropical dry forests|accessdate=2011-11-19}}</ref> |global200 = Yes<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.worldwildlife.org/science/ecoregions/WWFBinaryitem4810.pdf |format=PDF |first=David M. |last=Olson |author2=Eric Dinerstein |title=The Global 200: Priority Ecoregions for Global Conservation |journal=Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden |volume=89 |year=2002 |pages=199–224 |doi=10.2307/3298564}}</ref> |map = |map_size = |map_alt = |map_caption = }}
The '''Hawaiian tropical dry forests''' are a [[Tropical and subtropical dry broadleaf forests|tropical dry broadleaf forest]] [[ecoregion]] in the [[Hawaiian Islands]]. They cover an area of {{convert|6600|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} on the [[Windward and leeward|leeward]] side of the main islands and the summits of [[Niihau|Ni{{okina}}ihau]] and [[Kahoolawe|Kaho{{okina}}olawe]]. These forests are either seasonal or [[sclerophyll]]ous.<ref name="WWF"/> Annual rainfall is less than {{convert|127|cm|in|abbr=on}} and may be as low as {{convert|25|cm|in|abbr=on}};<ref name="WildWorld">{{NatGeo ecoregion|id=oc0202|name=Hawaii tropical dry forests|accessdate=2009-02-15}}</ref> the rainy season lasts from November to March.<ref name="UCLA">{{cite web |url=http://www.geog.ucla.edu/tdfpacific/hawaii.html |title=The Hawaiian Islands |work=Tropical Dry Forests of the Pacific |publisher=University of California, Los Angeles |accessdate=2009-02-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091224185058/http://www.geog.ucla.edu/tdfpacific/hawaii.html |archivedate=2009-12-24 |df= }}</ref> Dominant tree species include koa (''[[Acacia koa]]''), koai{{okina}}a (''[[Acacia koaia|A. koaia]]''), {{okina}}akoko (''[[Euphorbia]]'' spp.), {{okina}}ōhi{{okina}}a lehua (''[[Metrosideros polymorpha]]''), lonomea (''[[Sapindus oahuensis]]''), māmane (''[[Sophora chrysophylla]]''), loulu (''[[Pritchardia]]'' spp.), lama (''[[Diospyros sandwicensis]]''), olopua (''[[Nestegis sandwicensis]]''), wiliwili (''[[Erythrina sandwicensis]]''), and {{okina}}iliahi (''[[Santalum]]'' spp.). [[Endemism|Endemic]] plant species in the dry forests include hau hele{{okina}}ula (''[[Kokia cookei]]''), uhiuhi (''[[Caesalpinia kavaiensis]]''), and ''[[Gouania]]'' spp. The [[palila]] (''Loxioides bailleui''), a [[Hawaiian honeycreeper]], is restricted to this type of habitat.<ref name="WWF" />
==Prehistoric dry forests== The plant composition of Hawaii's dry forests has changed rather dramatically since the [[Ancient Hawaii|arrival]] of [[Polynesians]], excluding the deliberate introduction of non-native species.<ref name="UCLA"/> [[Fossil]]ized [[pollen]] has shown that loulu (''[[Pritchardia]]'' spp.) forests with an understory of Ka palupalu o Kanaloa (''[[Kanaloa kahoolawensis]]'') and {{okina}}a{{okina}}ali{{okina}}i (''[[Dodonaea viscosa]]'') existed on the islands' leeward lowlands<ref name="James_Prince">{{cite journal |title=Integration of palaeontological, historical, and geographical data on the extinction of koa-finches |first=Helen F. |last=James |author2=Johnathan P. Prince |journal=Diversity & Distributions |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=441–451 |date=May 2008 |url=http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/bsc/ddi/2008/00000014/00000003/art00001?crawler=true |doi=10.1111/j.1472-4642.2007.00442.x}}</ref> from at least before 1210 B.C. until 1565 A.D. Populations of loulu and {{okina}}a{{okina}}ali{{okina}}i still exist in diminished form, while only two Ka palupalu o Kanaloa specimens have ever been seen in the wild.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.floridata.com/tracks/bruce/raredelightsofHawaii.cfm |title=Rare Delights in Hawaiʻi |first=Bruce A. |last=Bohm |work=Floridata |accessdate=2009-02-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220124254/http://www.floridata.com/tracks/bruce/raredelightsofHawaii.cfm |archivedate=2008-12-20 |df= }}</ref>
==Maui== [[File:Auwahi Dryland Forest.JPG|thumb|Auwahi Dryland Forest]] The [[Auwahi Dryland Forest Restoration Project]] has produced a substantial forest on the slopes of [[Haleakala]] on the island of [[Maui]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mauitime.com/news/maui-koa/|title=Maui Koa|last=PARSONS|first=ROB|date=2007-04-12|work=Maui Time|access-date=2018-02-13|language=en-US}}</ref>
